        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aim to target the [CII] line emission line at z=5.1245, and hence require observations at 310.3 GHz (i.e. ALMA band 7). Our existing detection of the CO(2-1) line in J104043.50-115756.8 has a velocity FWHM of 110 km/s and, in the absence of further information, we assume that [CII] and CO(2-1) line emission trace the same range of velocities.  At this frequency, a line with FWHM~100 km/s will span &gt;100 MHz. Hence we chose a 2GHz bandwidth (i.e. relatively low spectral resolution) and expect to rebin and smooth over a number of channels.

As is the case with many high redshift galaxies, our information on the projected angular size of this source is limited. The CO line detection in J104043.50-115756.8 is an unresolved point source with a beam size of 7x5'' (45x30 kpc comoving at z~5), but this is many times larger than the projected size of any known (unlensed) z~5 galaxy suggesting that the true size is much smaller. Lyman break galaxies at this redshift have a characteristic size ~0.2'' in the optical. No optical detection exists for J104043.50-115756.8, and the possible near-infrared counterpart is also an unresolved point source, this time at sub-arcsecond resolution.

We thus make the assumption that J104043.50-115756.8 is an unresolved point source at the resolution of ALMA at this frequency (&lt;1.2'') as would be expected for Lyman break galaxies. Certainly it seems unlikely that emission exists on scales beyond the ~8'' largest scale as this should have been detectable even convolved with the beam of the ATCA. 

The RMS noise in our existing spectrum is ~4.5 mJy in 100 km/s channels. The formal flux measurement at our target frequency is 10.2+/-4.7 mJy. We propose to improve the depth of our existing observations by a factor of ten.  This would allow us to reach an L_CO/L_[CII] ratio a full dex below that expected for normal star forming galaxies (our current limit or 2 sigma measurement is somewhat low for a high redshift source but completely consistent with that ratio in local galaxies). This will yield either a ~10-20 sigma detection of the line or a definitive proof that it is not present together with a tight, physically meaningful upper limit.  We therefore require a 0.45\,mJy RMS integrated across the line  for a single pointing, assuming an unresolved point source, and conservatively assume a 50 km/s FWHM emission line.

The ALMA observing tool sensitivity calculator predicts an expected integration time of just 7.75 min on-source to reach this target depth, assuming dual polarisation, 34 antennae and calculator defaults for water vapour.

At the same time, we propose to use the full bandwidth available (4x1875 MHz) to obtain a continuum flux for this source with an rms of 69 uJy (based on the required time for the line experiment). This improves on our existing FIR continuum constraints from LABOCA (870 um) and MAMBO (1 mm) by factors of ~25 and ~7 respectively, and a non detection would imply a dust mass &lt;1.9 x 10^7 Msun at a temperature of 35 K and an extreme L_CO/L_FIR ratio (as figure 2 illustrates).

Given detections in CO, [CII] and the far-infrared continuum, we will be able to explore how this source compares to both local galaxies and high redshift sources in L_CO vs L_FIR (i.e. star formation efficiency), in L_[CII]/L_FIR vs L_FIR behaviour (which may be metallicity dependent, e.g. Maiolino et al 2009), and in the L_[CII]/L_FIR vs L_[CII]/L_FIR plane, which is diagnostic of both gas density and incident far-UV radiation (see for example De Breuck et al 2011).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
