    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>While great progress has been made in investigating galaxies at high redshifts (z&gt;5) over recent years, investigations have been limited to a few classes of objects. Unless a galaxy is dust-free and ultraviolet-luminous (Lyman break galaxies) or massive and intensely starbursting (SMGs or QSO hosts), it cannot identified by conventional techniques. However investigations at millimeter wavelengths have identified what may be the first galaxies of moderate mass and star formation intensity detected initially through molecular line emission.

Galaxy J104043.50-115756.8 at z=5.1245 exhibits CO(2-1) line emission at a redshift consistent with that of two neighbouring Lyman break galaxies. Here we propose observations at 310 GHz, probing the [CII] emission line at z=5 and the sub-millimetre flux in this source, tracing its cold neutral medium and constraining the gas density. Using ALMA it is possible to far exceed the sensitivity obtained in our previous work in a mere 8 min of integration time. In addition to unambiguously confirming the line redshift, in combination with our CO line detection we will constrain the dust emission and star formation intensity in this distant source.
</prp:abstract>
